After all that, and without repeating myself (I hope), my bottom line on this set is a resounding endorsement – this is a riveting collection of excellently crafted and thoroughly entertaining movies! I’m not a diehard fan of Westerns, but my appreciation has grown over the past decade or so, and these films are among the very best I’ve seen in that genre from its “classic” era. The themes they explore definitely transcend the usual white hat vs. black hat “horse opera” clichés, and each one delivers a distinctively satisfying experience without requiring much in the way of strenuous work to focus attention from the audience.

My only caveat would be for viewers who are decidedly uninterested in the Western genre – if you don’t get some degree of appreciation from watching men ride around on horses, pulling guns on each other, and settling their conflicts through high-stakes shootouts, these films are not meant for you. And I think it’s safe to assume that there’s a significant number of viewers who would cringe at some of the indisputably objectifying portrayals of women and indigenous peoples in several of the titles, though I don’t think they cross into territory that makes them actively offensive. Still, they are products of an era and a “man’s world” mentality that needs to be acknowledged in 2023. This set is already on my short list of “favorite Criterion releases of the year” and (setting the massive and magnificent Pasolini 101 edition aside), has a strong chance of being my #1 – though we have yet to see what November and December will unleash!

